msgid "You stumble out of Dr. Maleson's lab as tarry smoke fill the room behind you.  The physicist sprays a fire extinguisher in one continuous stream until mechanical wreckage can finally be seen in the gaps of the foam.  \"This is a total disaster...\" he groans, running one hand through his hair, \"practically back to square one... how could it have gone wrong so quickly?\"  You console Dr. Maleson in the aftermath, wondering if his machine was always doomed to failure, if there simply were factors he couldn't have known."
msgstr ""

msgid "The explosion of power rocks the lab, shaking loose several pieces of the failing machine.  One electrical coil tips over into another, showering the room in sparks and starting a domino cascade of destruction.  The geometric creature draws in the fading power, its tentacles coiling out in search of other sources as it depletes.  The tendrils tighten around Dr. Maleson, closest nearby as he tries desperately to save his machine from destruction.  He yells in terror as it seizes him, and he claws at loose machinery to pull himself away.  Before you can act, Dr. Maleson's device finally fails and goes dead.  A hideous noise rips through the air as the dimensions normalize, and the alien being scatters apart, along with the physicist still in its grip.  His final wail lingers in your ears in the empty stillness of the lab."
msgstr ""

msgid "Like the small cubes scattered throughout the earlier landscapes, the geometric being's death is startlingly quiet as its facets dim and it collapses down.  Dr. Maleson approaches the corpse with a mix of apprehension and scientific curiosity.  \"Is it organic or mechanical?  Or both?  How extraordinary!\"  He finishes powering down his device, still glancing at the alien over his shoulder.  \"There.  That should keep the overlap stable for study.\"  He plucks up a severed fragment with building excitement and places it in a glass bell on a smaller technical device.  \"We'll need to see if the sample maintains its integrity over a long period of time.  Take it with you for now.  I already have scads of other material to work with for now!  This could be the start of something even bigger than I ever imagined!\""
msgstr ""

msgid "Dr. Maleson quickly rises to his feet and rushes to the control panels of the machine.  \"Look, look!  Even fully shut off, there's still residual power from the overlap -- or that bizarre thing, or both!\"  He grabs a stop watch from a nearby drawer and begins running it while he records on his scratch pad gleefully.  \"It's a possibility I didn't even consider until now!  An entirely new form of energy!  I knew this'd be bigger than Einstein, but bigger than Edison?  Oh, if only I'd known sooner!\"  He turns to you, looking half mad from joy.  \"I'll have to reinforce my machine of course, and prepare for any similar surprises, but this was a resounding success!\"  The physicist hands you a small gauge with the same odd energy running through it.  \"Now if you'd do me one last favor, I want you to take this with you.  The gauge is attuned to this energy, and will help you survey hotspots for future attempts!\""
msgstr ""
